 century to 1922. Their stories, narratives and histories illustrate the emergence of Irish journalism chronicling the evolution and development of the profession, and the various challenges confronted by the first generation of modern journalists.The profession’s past is framed by reference to its practitioners and their practice. Readers are treated to studies of foreign correspondents, editorial writers, provincial newspaper owners, sports journalists and the challenges of minority language journalism. The volume goes beyond Ireland to explore the work of Irish journalists abroad and shows how the great political debates about Ireland’s place in the United Kingdom served as a backdrop to newspaper publication in the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries.In his preface Professor James Curran concludes that the volume “advances by leaps and bounds the history of the Irish press”.The collection makes valuable and important contribution to our knowledge of Irish journalism - and like all good reportage it offers its readers a very good read.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJournalismzIrelandxHistoryy19th century. 0aJournalismzIrelandxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Irish Treaty.  aChicago.  aFinley Peter Dunne.  aFreeman's Journal.  aIrish Independent.  aIrish War of Independence.  aIrish journalism.  aJohn F. Finerty.  aMargaret Sullivan.  aMelville E. Stone.  aSinn Fein.  aSkibbereen Eagle.  aThe Irish Times.  aTsar of Russia.  aUnited Kingdom.  aWilliam Howard Russell.  apeace process.  apolitical debates.1 aBrillman, M.L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurran, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoley, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https:/